1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:28,400
 That people don't realize it.The Bitcoin plays.Nobody ever wastes a thought on it.You need to be sure that what you're taking here is the real thing and not something that is a scam.The need of governments to pay for their expenses made governments very inventive. Suddenly everybody realizes, wait, kak je toj svetak skupo?The badge? I don't trust any statistic that I haven't forged myself.

2
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:32,400
 How do you get to know about it?

3
00:00:32,400 --> 00:00:59,400
 Hello everyone, welcome to another episode of Horizons of Leadership.Today we are happy to have with us Professor Peter Schmidt.Peter is a senior lecturer at RIT Croatia with over 13 years of experience in teaching.His expertise in accounting, taxation,inflation,money and Bitcoin have not just had a big impact on myself personally,but on a large number of other students as well.

4
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:09,000
 As a mentor of a Bitcoin club at RIT,he has inspired and guided a number of students in exploring this technology.Professor Schmidt,I'm so happy to have you with us today.

5
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:27,000
 Thank you for having me and I'm glad to hear all this and great that you're doing this podcast.So Professor,you invented the whole one course at RIT called Money, Inflation and Bitcoin.You've been speaker on a number of conferences and you've been club mentor for over 50 students.

6
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:34,000
 Can you tell me like what what is driving you and on what mission are you right now?

7
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:54,000
 I realized when I understood how Bitcoin works that this needs to be seen in the wider context of how money works.Money is a weird thing.We use it all the time every day and nobody ever wastes a thought on it.

8
00:01:54,000 --> 00:02:21,000
 We just kind of think it works the way it should work until we actually start looking a little deeper and so after Bitcoin came around there was a reason to examine how money works because we had now an alternative.So that is something I understood, I studied and I think that is something that students, particularly students of business but any young person needs to understand how money works.

9
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:28,000
 and what alternatives there are.So that's the motivation and the mission.

10
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:36,000
 Yes, of course.Can we start from the scratch, like from the beginning. How would you define money and what purpose does it actually serve?

11
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:48,000
 One of my favourite pictures in beginning presentations is a picture of the Neanderthal Museum in Krapina.

12
00:02:48,000 --> 00:03:02,000
 So there is a scene in the museum of a bunch of people comfortably in their cave and essentially they have nothing but a little bit of fur pelts and maybe some simple tools and here they are.

13
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:06,000
 And so I put up this slide and I ask my students, so what's missing here?

14
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:11,000
 This is like the vicinity of Zagreb. This is like less than an hour away from Zagreb.

15
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:26,000
 It doesn't look like that anymore today. And then we realize everything is missing, all the stuff that we consider normal in our life, starting with clothes, with beds, with apartments, with furniture.

16
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:33,000
 And so we wonder, how is this made? How did we ever get from the cave to our modern life?

17
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:43,000
 Well, the answer is simple. Somebody built all these things, but not one person can do this all.

18
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:50,000
 It needs the cooperation, the coordinated cooperation of many people.

19
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:54,000
 Many people specialize, increase their productivity at what they're doing.

20
00:03:54,000 --> 00:03:58,000
 They produce clothes, but then at some point they will need food.

21
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:02,000
 So there is a need for exchange and now we're getting to the money.

22
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:14,000
 If we do exchange one thing for another, what is called barter, that is tremendously tedious if it ever worked.

23
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:17,000
 Anthropologists discuss this.

24
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:31,000
 If we manage to introduce an intermediate exchange technology, like let's say a token that represents value and everybody agrees on that.

25
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:37,000
 That would make coordination a lot easier and that is what money does.

26
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:52,000
 So instead of exchanging your cow for 700 deliveries of bread, you can now take tokens for your cow.

27
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:56,000
 And then whenever you're ready, you can buy bread as you like.

28
00:04:56,000 --> 00:05:04,000
 So we have effectively decoupled one barter into two trades and that is the cool thing about money.

29
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:10,000
 It enables the coordination very efficiently if it is good money.

30
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:17,000
 Can you maybe tell us like what are the core characteristics that make something called money?

31
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:19,000
 That money needs to have in order to be money?

32
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:27,000
 So many things can be money in more or less of a qualified way.

33
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:37,000
 Money is nothing that is ever given to people, but money is a technology that is emergent among people.

34
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:40,000
 People discover that something works as money.

35
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:46,000
 And over the history, we have many colorful examples of things that served as money.

36
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:52,000
 In the end, it turned out that gold was a really good token.

37
00:05:52,000 --> 00:06:02,000
 Before that we had glossy seashells, wampum shells, kauri shells that worked great, glass beads that worked well.

38
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:10,000
 All these things will work to some extent as money in as much as they fulfill monetary properties.

39
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:11,000
 Great.

40
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:14,000
 So what is like today's money?

41
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:17,000
 Can you compare today's money and how was it in the past?

42
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:25,000
 You said we had a trade-off for like people were trading off cows for some goods and then we have this misception.

43
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:27,000
 So can you kind of touch on that?

44
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:29,000
 Like how is it today and how was it in the past?

45
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:33,000
 Yeah, so this boils down to monetary properties.

46
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:37,000
 What kind of properties does the money we use have?

47
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:39,000
 And those are few.

48
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:44,000
 I mean, I like to limit the list to five in my classes.

49
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:48,000
 The money that works well needs to be divisible.

50
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:52,000
 So you cannot exchange a cow against a loaf of bread.

51
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:55,000
 You need something more finely grained.

52
00:06:55,000 --> 00:06:57,000
 It needs to be durable.

53
00:06:57,000 --> 00:07:01,000
 So it needs to last also until next year maybe.

54
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:06,000
 Or maybe even until your retirement if you want to save for that.

55
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:09,000
 Then it needs to be transportable.

56
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:15,000
 You need to be able to take it along with you because you might want to spend it in the next town.

57
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:19,000
 And then it needs to be recognizable.

58
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:25,000
 You need to be sure that what you're taking here is the real thing and not something that is a scam.

59
00:07:25,000 --> 00:07:32,000
 But the most important one I saved for last and that is it needs to be scarce.

60
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:39,000
 We can use glossy seashells for money which are hard to find.

61
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:43,000
 But we cannot use pebbles that we find on the beach.

62
00:07:43,000 --> 00:07:47,000
 Because that defies the purpose of facilitating the exchange.

63
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:58,000
 Now over time many of the monies that humanity has used have fulfilled these properties in one way or another.

64
00:07:58,000 --> 00:08:00,000
 Better or worse.

65
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:10,000
 But somehow over the last hundred years or so we ended up with paper money and with digital numbers on computer screens.

66
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:17,000
 Now those are really good at most of the monetary properties except one.

67
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:21,000
 They failed miserably in terms of scarcity.

68
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:29,000
 Because they can be produced at will and that is what causes a lot of economic problems in our lives today.

69
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:34,000
 You mentioned that the gold was a good monetary policy.

70
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:42,000
 So can you just touch on that like why is the gold a good one and why did we transfer from gold to money that we know today?

71
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:51,000
 Well gold is a reasonably good one and it was a good one particularly in times where mobility was not the main issue.

72
00:08:51,000 --> 00:08:52,000
 Gold is a good one.

73
00:08:52,000 --> 00:09:01,000
 Gold is scarce however it has deficiencies in the context of divisibility.

74
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:04,000
 Now go buy a sandwich with gold.

75
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:07,000
 It must be a very small piece of gold.

76
00:09:07,000 --> 00:09:10,000
 Very hard to even verify that it is gold.

77
00:09:10,000 --> 00:09:14,000
 Then recognizability is not a strong side of gold.

78
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:18,000
 So here is a gold bar you tell me.

79
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:20,000
 How do I know this is really gold?

80
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:25,000
 How do I know it is not only gold around it and inside it is some cheap metal?

81
00:09:25,000 --> 00:09:29,000
 Yeah I could find that out if I had a laboratory.

82
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:35,000
 But it is not a very easy thing to do in everyday trading.

83
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:38,000
 And then another aspect is the weight.

84
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:46,000
 So go carry around or transfer a million dollars worth in gold and that will be a major endeavor.

85
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:49,000
 Not only to transport it but also to secure it.

86
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:54,000
 Let alone that it is physical and you need to move it from here to there.

87
00:09:54,000 --> 00:09:58,000
 Much unlike immaterial ways of money.

88
00:09:58,000 --> 00:10:07,000
 When we talk about gold we have one interesting story about the German kid that bring the gold bars to the bank and sold them and they didn't even realize.

89
00:10:07,000 --> 00:10:10,000
 They just realized after like some time after.

90
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:13,000
 That was a story I shared in the lecture yes.

91
00:10:13,000 --> 00:10:20,000
 And that is always interesting because indeed a real case I believe in 2015-2016.

92
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:29,000
 a German kid age 18 at the time actually managed to sell several gold bars to his local bank.

93
00:10:29,000 --> 00:10:32,000
 And the local bank was fine with that.

94
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:35,000
 He came up with a story of a grandma.

95
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:44,000
 And he never told that he got the money, I mean the gold, at eBay for a few dollars.

96
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:49,000
 And it took weeks or months for the bank to figure out that they had been had.

97
00:10:49,000 --> 00:10:53,000
 So, so much about the recognizability of gold.

98
00:10:53,000 --> 00:11:00,000
 So, today we have transferred from gold and we have something called monetary system, fiat money.

99
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:06,000
 Can you explain us how does today's monetary system actually function and how does it serve to us?

100
00:11:06,000 --> 00:11:18,000
 So, we make a very big jump now from exchanging gold in sort of pre-modern times to monetary systems as they have emerged

101
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:20,000
 during the 19th and 20th century.

102
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:22,000
 How have they emerged?

103
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:35,000
 They have emerged in the sense that the need of governments to pay for their expenses made governments very inventive.

104
00:11:35,000 --> 00:11:47,000
 And inventive in the sense that they have decided that they will put the whole monetary system of their country under their control through a central bank and an underlying bank.

105
00:11:47,000 --> 00:12:02,000
 So, essentially without having much material here let's imagine the issuance of money as a balance sheet.

106
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:09,000
 On the liability side is the money and on the asset side is something that backs this money.

107
00:12:09,000 --> 00:12:21,000
 And that used to be gold and even in early central banks like let's say a hundred plus years ago that used to be what balance sheets of central banks looked like.

108
00:12:21,000 --> 00:12:33,000
 But then the desire for spending more money was too big to resist for governments.

109
00:12:33,000 --> 00:12:48,000
 So, instead of respecting the limit of the gold which at a certain exchange rate gold to dollars or gold to fiat currency in general terms would limit the amount of money that could be issued.

110
00:12:48,000 --> 00:12:53,000
 They secretly made more, made more, made more and made more.

111
00:12:53,000 --> 00:12:57,000
 And so, the liability side of that balance sheet kept growing.

112
00:12:57,000 --> 00:13:03,000
 They making people believe that it's all good, here's the gold, here's the money.

113
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:08,000
 But like every scam at some point it blows up.

114
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:32,000
 And in the case of central banks and the gold standard that was in 1971 when the bluff was called and Richard Nixon then president of the United States had to suspend the convertibility of dollars into gold at given exchange rates which still existed at that time at the nation state level.

115
00:13:32,000 --> 00:13:47,000
 So, ever since then gold as the asset disappeared in the central bank balance sheets and was replaced by another asset, government debt.

116
00:13:47,000 --> 00:13:59,000
 So, debt is the debt of the person who took the money but the person who invested into this debt, for them the debt is an asset.

117
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:02,000
 So, if you buy treasury bonds, you have an asset.

118
00:14:02,000 --> 00:14:06,000
 So, if you buy treasury bonds, you have an asset.

119
00:14:06,000 --> 00:14:12,000
 If the Federal Reserve Bank holds treasury bonds, it holds an asset.

120
00:14:12,000 --> 00:14:15,000
 So, that asset now backs the money.

121
00:14:15,000 --> 00:14:20,000
 It has one amazing quality though.

122
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:22,000
 You can very easily make more of it.

123
00:14:22,000 --> 00:14:38,000
 So, essentially 1971 when the gold backing was given up for good, that meant that there was no limit to how long the Federal Reserve balance sheet could grow.

124
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:47,000
 And it has grown and grown and grown and grown and grown and grown and grown again in COVID to unbelievable proportions.

125
00:14:47,000 --> 00:14:52,000
 If you look at the charts, you'd be like, what is this? A scan?

126
00:14:53,000 --> 00:14:56,000
 Nobody sees those charts, nobody looks at those charts.

127
00:14:56,000 --> 00:15:02,000
 It's almost like you don't want to know the truth.

128
00:15:02,000 --> 00:15:10,000
 But the truth is kind of slowly fermenting on the back burner and we're wondering where this will lead.

129
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:23,000
 What are some risks to this? Like, we have it connected to debt and what risk? Is it inflation? Is it just this debt, centralization?

130
00:15:23,000 --> 00:15:25,000
 What's the risk of today's monetary system?

131
00:15:25,000 --> 00:15:50,000
 So, if we use money, fiat money as we have today in the form of paper, which is the smallest amount and then in the form of electronic money on bank computers, so to speak, then the biggest problem here is that the amount of it grows and grows and grows and grows and with the amount grows the debt.

132
00:15:50,000 --> 00:15:57,000
 Because all money, all money is debt in an accounting sense.

133
00:15:57,000 --> 00:16:02,000
 And that is very obvious if you dig deeper and it is not at all a secret.

134
00:16:02,000 --> 00:16:12,000
 You can read a beautiful article of 2014 of the Bank of England where they lay it out in much detail in their quarterly bulletin.

135
00:16:12,000 --> 00:16:19,000
 Anyone can find that easily by Googling 2014 quarterly bulletin of the Bank of England.

136
00:16:19,000 --> 00:16:24,000
 Read through those very dense articles and you will know all the accounting behind it.

137
00:16:24,000 --> 00:16:31,000
 It is essentially an unlimited method of producing more and more money.

138
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:36,000
 And producing more and more money has a bunch of unpleasant consequences.

139
00:16:36,000 --> 00:16:40,000
 First of all, there is more money.

140
00:16:40,000 --> 00:16:49,000
 But that money was not created by producing more stuff and selling that like you would usually have to earn your money.

141
00:16:49,000 --> 00:16:55,000
 If you want to spend money, you have to produce something to the economy so that you get that money.

142
00:16:55,000 --> 00:17:07,000
 Now, if you were somebody who could just print money, essentially go to the copy machine and copy whatever you have in your wallet today and then go shopping with those copies.

143
00:17:07,000 --> 00:17:08,000
 What have you done?

144
00:17:08,000 --> 00:17:16,000
 You are taking out because the money is essentially a voucher for you to claim real goods and real services from the economy.

145
00:17:16,000 --> 00:17:21,000
 But you have not pitched in anything.

146
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:36,000
 That means you are now creating demand in the economy and that means your demand is additional demand to the demand that already existed before.

147
00:17:36,000 --> 00:17:44,000
 Now, if we have more money chasing the unchanged amount of real goods and services, then what will happen?

148
00:17:44,000 --> 00:17:46,000
 The prices will go up.

149
00:17:46,000 --> 00:17:52,000
 And that is also something that has been known for centuries.

150
00:17:52,000 --> 00:18:02,000
 I have just recently discovered a beautiful book from the late 19th century about the American currency, history of the American currency.

151
00:18:02,000 --> 00:18:07,000
 And the author lays this out in simple terms very clearly.

152
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:09,000
 I think the book is from 1867.

153
00:18:09,000 --> 00:18:16,000
 Milton Friedman is on tape saying this in the 1970s.

154
00:18:16,000 --> 00:18:22,000
 The Nobel Prize winner, a monetarist of Milton Friedman.

155
00:18:22,000 --> 00:18:30,000
 Nothing of that is secret or nothing of that should be unknown, but nobody wants to hear that somehow.

156
00:18:30,000 --> 00:18:40,000
 Until now, where we suddenly struggle with inflation, suddenly everybody realizes, wait, kakito svetak skupo?

157
00:18:40,000 --> 00:18:50,000
 And a little while ago, a cake cost 19 kuna and now it costs the equivalent of 35 kuna or something like that.

158
00:18:50,000 --> 00:18:55,000
 So, that is the consequence of what we're facing.

159
00:18:55,000 --> 00:19:02,000
 And there is one more consequence that is essentially the same effect.

160
00:19:02,000 --> 00:19:09,000
 If you understand the system, it's very easy to avoid the disadvantages.

161
00:19:09,000 --> 00:19:13,000
 But if you don't understand the system, you suffer.

162
00:19:13,000 --> 00:19:16,000
 Now, who understands the system?

163
00:19:16,000 --> 00:19:19,000
 Of course, those people who are deeply in the system.

164
00:19:19,000 --> 00:19:21,000
 That means rich people.

165
00:19:21,000 --> 00:19:32,000
 If you're rich, it'll be very easy for you to avoid the unpleasant effects of inflation because you can play them in your favor.

166
00:19:32,000 --> 00:19:42,000
 If the value of money declines, well, then how about you have negative value of money and that means you go into debt.

167
00:19:42,000 --> 00:19:44,000
 Then that debt will also decline.

168
00:19:44,000 --> 00:19:53,000
 All the while feeding your hard assets that you bought with collateralized debt because you're rich.

169
00:19:53,000 --> 00:19:59,000
 And so, inflation will make you richer and richer and richer if you play the system.

170
00:19:59,000 --> 00:20:07,000
 Just like it makes other people poorer and poorer and poorer that cannot play the system because A, they don't understand it.

171
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:14,000
 And B, if they did understand it, they wouldn't have the collateral to play it in a big scope.

172
00:20:14,000 --> 00:20:20,000
 Can we say that inflation is then taxed to poor people?

173
00:20:20,000 --> 00:20:22,000
 It works the same way, essentially.

174
00:20:22,000 --> 00:20:31,000
 So, you earn 5,000, you pay 2,500 in tax and you can spend 2,500.

175
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:40,000
 The insidious aspect of taking people's purchase money through inflation is that people don't realize it.

176
00:20:40,000 --> 00:20:42,000
 So, you have 5,000.

177
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:48,000
 You still have 5,000 next month, but the 5,000 buy you less.

178
00:20:48,000 --> 00:20:57,000
 Maybe after 2 years, after 3 years, after 7 years, they will buy you half of what 5,000 used to buy.

179
00:20:57,000 --> 00:21:02,000
 Now, the irony why nobody gets this is because you still have 5,000.

180
00:21:02,000 --> 00:21:12,000
 Would you say that today is like there's a lot of manipulation with data, especially government, like in the way when we talk about inflation,

181
00:21:12,000 --> 00:21:17,000
 they like to say, oh, inflation dropped down to 2-3% or something like that.

182
00:21:17,000 --> 00:21:22,000
 But like if we look in the past, it has just grown and grown and grown.

183
00:21:22,000 --> 00:21:27,000
 You may have heard the old adage, I don't trust any statistic that I haven't forged myself.

184
00:21:27,000 --> 00:21:37,000
 So, the way inflation is officially measured by consumer price, inflation indexes and so forth

185
00:21:37,000 --> 00:21:46,000
 is a highly, highly stylized way of coming up with numbers that are as low as humanly possible,

186
00:21:46,000 --> 00:21:51,000
 to hide as much of inflation as they can.

187
00:21:51,000 --> 00:22:01,000
 Now, in fact, what we should be seeing with technical progress, and I mentioned the increase of productivity a little while ago in our conversation,

188
00:22:01,000 --> 00:22:08,000
 technical progress should make us all more productive, should make us all be able to produce more things.

189
00:22:08,000 --> 00:22:12,000
 If we have more things, the prices of things should go down.

190
00:22:12,000 --> 00:22:18,000
 So, even constant prices would already be an anomaly.

191
00:22:18,000 --> 00:22:24,000
 We face rising prices, and that is an indication of how much we're cheated through the monetary system

192
00:22:24,000 --> 00:22:33,000
 by institutions that produce more vouchers that enable them to buy goods than were ever produced in that economy.

193
00:22:33,000 --> 00:22:37,000
 And that is how people are stolen from effectively.

194
00:22:37,000 --> 00:22:50,000
 How people are taxed in that inflation tax that is invisible but very noticeable in your wallet from month to month.

195
00:22:50,000 --> 00:22:56,000
 Government uses the word inflation, but if I understood well, the big problem is in the supply.

196
00:22:56,000 --> 00:23:00,000
 The amount of money that they bring into the system and offer to people, right?

197
00:23:00,000 --> 00:23:11,000
 So, that is what causes the whole problem, that you can create more money very easily to fulfill all the things you've promised.

198
00:23:11,000 --> 00:23:18,000
 Governments love to promise things because they love to be re-elected, because they love the position of power

199
00:23:18,000 --> 00:23:21,000
 and of being in control of everything.

200
00:23:21,000 --> 00:23:31,000
 So, if you make lots of promises and if you cause lots of expenses, and last not least, war is a huge government expense

201
00:23:31,000 --> 00:23:36,000
 that can only be financed through central banks, jump back.

202
00:23:36,000 --> 00:23:46,000
 That was one of the reasons why central banking was invented in the 17th century to facilitate war spending in order,

203
00:23:46,000 --> 00:23:55,000
 well, essentially to steal from people the productive output of their work in order to redirect it into war economy.

204
00:23:55,000 --> 00:24:05,000
 So, those are the reasons why we essentially face that huge amount of money that causes the price inflation.

205
00:24:05,000 --> 00:24:08,000
 So, we should really use two words.

206
00:24:08,000 --> 00:24:12,000
 We should use the monetary inflation, which means the monetary quantity gets blown up,

207
00:24:12,000 --> 00:24:21,000
 and then the consequence of that will be the price inflation because more goods, sorry, more money chases the same goods.

208
00:24:21,000 --> 00:24:25,000
 So, on one side we have money supply, on the other side we have debt.

209
00:24:25,000 --> 00:24:28,000
 As money supply increases, does this debt increase?

210
00:24:28,000 --> 00:24:33,000
 The debt increases because the debt is the backing of the money.

211
00:24:33,000 --> 00:24:36,000
 So, think back to what I said about the balance sheet.

212
00:24:36,000 --> 00:24:41,000
 The balance sheet is no longer gold on the asset side, money on the liability side,

213
00:24:41,000 --> 00:24:48,000
 but the assets are now government debt, which is an asset seen from the other side of the metal,

214
00:24:48,000 --> 00:24:51,000
 and money on the other side.

215
00:24:51,000 --> 00:25:01,000
 So, that is why we see those unbelievably increasing sovereign debt numbers and that is stunning.

216
00:25:01,000 --> 00:25:05,000
 If you look at it, there is one illustration I love to use.

217
00:25:05,000 --> 00:25:14,000
 The last 125 years of US sovereign debt and the graph looks like the Burj Khalifa.

218
00:25:14,000 --> 00:25:17,000
 So, like that.

219
00:25:17,000 --> 00:25:20,000
 And we're at 36 trillion now, which is unbelievable.

220
00:25:20,000 --> 00:25:30,000
 In that same graph, you see that it took the United States about 200 years to reach 1 trillion of national sovereign debt.

221
00:25:30,000 --> 00:25:36,000
 From 1 trillion to 36 trillion, it took only about 45 years.

222
00:25:36,000 --> 00:25:46,000
 So, you might ask where is this going to end or what is the limit of that?

223
00:25:46,000 --> 00:25:48,000
 We don't know.

224
00:25:48,000 --> 00:25:54,000
 The one thing we do know is that it always lasts longer than we think.

225
00:25:54,000 --> 00:26:03,000
 So, whenever a company is about to go bankrupt, it lasts for much longer than you think.

226
00:26:03,000 --> 00:26:07,000
 Whenever something is coming to an end, it might drag on for longer.

227
00:26:07,000 --> 00:26:13,000
 Just the end of the Soviet Union and its associated economies come to my mind.

228
00:26:13,000 --> 00:26:22,000
 We all thought this was going to last forever, even though everybody knew that these economies were not sustainable.

229
00:26:22,000 --> 00:26:31,000
 And then it ended overnight on November 9th of 1989, for the Germans at least.

230
00:26:31,000 --> 00:26:39,000
 So, everything might last forever, it seems.

231
00:26:39,000 --> 00:26:41,000
 And then it might collapse very quickly.

232
00:26:41,000 --> 00:26:46,000
 However, don't dare to forecast when this will happen.

233
00:26:46,000 --> 00:26:49,000
 It will probably drag on for longer than we think.

234
00:26:49,000 --> 00:26:56,000
 So, we cannot know like exact time when this like say financial crash will happen.

235
00:26:56,000 --> 00:26:59,000
 And like how far...

236
00:26:59,000 --> 00:27:02,000
 Well, we don't even know if there will be a financial crash.

237
00:27:02,000 --> 00:27:10,000
 See, this is all stuff that never happened before.

238
00:27:10,000 --> 00:27:15,000
 And it will be really hard to forecast anything here.

239
00:27:15,000 --> 00:27:24,000
 The only thing what we can say is that the way it is going, it is going into absolute absurdity.

240
00:27:24,000 --> 00:27:34,000
 Because 36 trillion dollars are, for example, an amount that is so absurdly high that nobody can actually expect that this will ever be paid back.

241
00:27:34,000 --> 00:27:36,000
 This will just be rolled on.

242
00:27:36,000 --> 00:27:37,000
 It will increase.

243
00:27:37,000 --> 00:27:41,000
 It will have to increase to more because of the nature of this debt.

244
00:27:41,000 --> 00:27:42,000
 So, it will never go down.

245
00:27:42,000 --> 00:27:43,000
 It will always go up.

246
00:27:43,000 --> 00:27:47,000
 Now, the question is what will happen if it goes up?

247
00:27:47,000 --> 00:27:48,000
 Will it still be used?

248
00:27:48,000 --> 00:27:53,000
 The dollar could be used arguably as a medium of exchange.

249
00:27:53,000 --> 00:27:58,000
 It will just entirely lose any purpose as a store of value.

250
00:27:58,000 --> 00:28:02,000
 So, there may also be a non-catastrophic end to that.

251
00:28:02,000 --> 00:28:08,000
 Just a sort of quiet transition into another system.

252
00:28:08,000 --> 00:28:21,000
 What are some challenges, like I as a young individual, that time is ahead of me, like what are some issues that I am facing right now with this system?

253
00:28:21,000 --> 00:28:25,000
 Your issue is that you will have a hard time building wealth.

254
00:28:25,000 --> 00:28:39,000
 Your parents or former generations started when they were 18 also with essentially nothing but their wits and their power.

255
00:28:39,000 --> 00:28:45,000
 And then they could build step by step some wealth.

256
00:28:45,000 --> 00:28:46,000
 They could acquire land.

257
00:28:46,000 --> 00:28:48,000
 They could acquire a house.

258
00:28:48,000 --> 00:28:52,000
 They could equip their household and so forth.

259
00:28:52,000 --> 00:28:59,000
 This is fine as long as nobody takes the purchasing power out of your pocket that you've just worked for.

260
00:28:59,000 --> 00:29:01,000
 This is now a new feature.

261
00:29:01,000 --> 00:29:14,000
 You, as young people, will have to face that you will have to run in the hamster wheel to just stay on one position, let alone to acquire wealth.

262
00:29:14,000 --> 00:29:22,000
 And that will be very frustrating and very unsettling for the young generation.

263
00:29:22,000 --> 00:29:27,000
 That is why we spoke about this as the mission at the beginning of our talk.

264
00:29:27,000 --> 00:29:30,000
 Why this is so important for young people to understand.

265
00:29:30,000 --> 00:29:34,000
 That they are being had by the system.

266
00:29:34,000 --> 00:29:37,000
 You mentioned that we get in this hamster wheel.

267
00:29:37,000 --> 00:29:47,000
 Is there a solution that we get out of it and that in different way we create our wealth and to not constantly be in this wheel, to get some kind of out of it?

268
00:29:47,000 --> 00:29:56,000
 So the question would be, or the answer to this question would be, how can I preserve my purchasing power?

269
00:29:56,000 --> 00:30:03,000
 And the rich people I mentioned before are using, for example, real estate for that.

270
00:30:03,000 --> 00:30:11,000
 However, we have a better solution since 2009 and that is hard money in the form of Bitcoin.

271
00:30:11,000 --> 00:30:16,000
 So Bitcoin is the invention of digital scarcity.

272
00:30:16,000 --> 00:30:22,000
 Digital scarcity is almost an eximilaron because if it's digital, it can be copied freely.

273
00:30:22,000 --> 00:30:29,000
 But for the first time, we now have a form of digital scarcity in the Bitcoin protocol.

274
00:30:29,000 --> 00:30:35,000
 And that makes this digital scarcity uniquely usable as money.

275
00:30:35,000 --> 00:30:52,000
 So by using hard money in the form of Bitcoin, you have essentially an escape hatch, as Christine Lagarde called it, from the fiat system.

276
00:30:52,000 --> 00:31:00,000
 You can no longer be stolen from if your wealth is not kept in euros or in US dollars.

277
00:31:00,000 --> 00:31:05,000
 And that is where education needs to lead you as young people.

278
00:31:05,000 --> 00:31:09,000
 And that is what I see as my job.

279
00:31:09,000 --> 00:31:14,000
 Can you explain more like from perspective, something to be money, it needs to have value.

280
00:31:14,000 --> 00:31:17,000
 So why does Bitcoin have value?

281
00:31:17,000 --> 00:31:19,000
 Very easy to explain.

282
00:31:19,000 --> 00:31:25,000
 Let's come back to the monetary properties that we spoke about a while ago.

283
00:31:25,000 --> 00:31:28,000
 So I said I usually refer to five of them.

284
00:31:28,000 --> 00:31:32,000
 You could enumerate more, but let's stick with five.

285
00:31:32,000 --> 00:31:38,000
 Bitcoin in every single one is better than all its competitors.

286
00:31:38,000 --> 00:31:41,000
 It is super divisible.

287
00:31:41,000 --> 00:31:53,000
 It is durable, because as long as the Bitcoin protocol runs, and that means as long as we have electricity and the internet to communicate on, Bitcoin will work just fine.

288
00:31:53,000 --> 00:32:05,000
 Then it is portable as easily as an electron through the ether.

289
00:32:05,000 --> 00:32:21,000
 And then finally, it is recognizable because whether you do or you do not hold a chunk of Bitcoin will be determined by the Bitcoin protocol itself without any doubt.

290
00:32:21,000 --> 00:32:25,000
 And finally, of course, the most important one is SCARS.

291
00:32:25,000 --> 00:32:39,000
 If you understand the technology, you will understand that its supply is credibly limited to these 21 million or 2.1 quadrillion Satoshis if we look at the lower unit.

292
00:32:39,000 --> 00:32:46,000
 And just in case anybody worries, those Satoshis could be subdivided further if need be.

293
00:32:46,000 --> 00:32:57,000
 For example, as we do already on the level 2 of Bitcoin, the lightning network, where we actually have the possibility of accounting for micro Satoshis.

294
00:32:57,000 --> 00:33:01,000
 That means a thousandth of a Satoshi.

295
00:33:01,000 --> 00:33:10,000
 When we talk about, we mentioned some problems as inflation, debt, centralized system.

296
00:33:10,000 --> 00:33:13,000
 How does Bitcoin solve these problems in the way?

297
00:33:13,000 --> 00:33:15,000
 How does it acquire wealth?

298
00:33:15,000 --> 00:33:17,000
 And is there something that we don't see?

299
00:33:17,000 --> 00:33:22,000
 Bitcoin is not a debt backed money.

300
00:33:22,000 --> 00:33:25,000
 It is a bearer asset.

301
00:33:25,000 --> 00:33:27,000
 And that makes all the difference.

302
00:33:27,000 --> 00:33:40,000
 So since it fulfills those five monetary qualities so incredibly well, people use it for the reason that I sketched at the very beginning to coordinate their exchange.

303
00:33:40,000 --> 00:33:50,000
 Everybody is specialized, everybody needs to trade their goods for other goods and for that Bitcoin works tremendously well.

304
00:33:50,000 --> 00:33:56,000
 It literally is the best store of value that we can imagine.

305
00:33:56,000 --> 00:34:04,000
 Michael Saylor always says Bitcoin is Manhattan in cyberspace.

306
00:34:04,000 --> 00:34:13,000
 So it is like buying a block of Manhattan before Manhattan became what it is today.

307
00:34:13,000 --> 00:34:25,000
 So it is a supremely qualified store of value and over time will acquire the other monetary functions as well.

308
00:34:25,000 --> 00:34:30,000
 You can use it as a medium of exchange today.

309
00:34:30,000 --> 00:34:37,000
 I have used it two weeks ago at a Bitcoin conference to buy coffee and I regret it already.

310
00:34:37,000 --> 00:34:50,000
 So while we are in this dramatically dynamic adoption phase of Bitcoin where it acquires value through more people joining the Bitcoin network,

311
00:34:50,000 --> 00:35:05,000
 it's no fun to use it as a means of exchange because what I paid in the beginning of November for my coffee is probably twice as much or I don't know how much it went up.

312
00:35:05,000 --> 00:35:11,000
 Important information, Bitcoin going up in value is not the reason why we are interested in Bitcoin.

313
00:35:11,000 --> 00:35:20,000
 We are interested in it as the monetary alternative that allows fair exchange between all its participants.

314
00:35:20,000 --> 00:35:26,000
 You mentioned Michael Saylor. Can you give us some examples how does he leverage Bitcoin for his company?

315
00:35:26,000 --> 00:35:32,000
 And can you give us are there examples of government leveraging it or some other companies that they do?

316
00:35:32,000 --> 00:35:51,000
 Michael Saylor is a very remarkable man in that he was the first businessman to discover the incredible potential that Bitcoin has as a store of value and as a treasury reserve asset on a corporate level.

317
00:35:51,000 --> 00:36:10,000
 That was in summer of 2020 and ever since then he has systematically transformed his company MicroStrategy into a Bitcoin holding company that has literally changed the nature of this company.

318
00:36:10,000 --> 00:36:19,000
 In the course of which he also made MicroStrategy the best performing American stock.

319
00:36:19,000 --> 00:36:31,000
 Something that goes largely unnoticed by the broader public and so everybody wonders if he is so successful with it why doesn't everybody do it?

320
00:36:31,000 --> 00:36:41,000
 Well, one of the reasons is you need to understand it and that requires 100 hours as he says to understand Bitcoin the asset.

321
00:36:41,000 --> 00:36:57,000
 And then you need to be able to do it in your company because you will have to convince a number of levels of decision makers in a normal corporate governance structure.

322
00:36:57,000 --> 00:37:03,000
 In the case of MicroStrategy he was at an advantage because he was the founder and still the majority owner.

323
00:37:03,000 --> 00:37:19,000
 So that went a lot smoother than it would go in a broadly held company like the huge companies that everybody thinks of that have literally billions of cash that could be transferred into a better asset.

324
00:37:19,000 --> 00:37:25,000
 But is not because it is hard to bring everybody in a row on this topic.

325
00:37:25,000 --> 00:37:35,000
 Now you mentioned states, obviously what works on the corporate level would work on the state level.

326
00:37:35,000 --> 00:37:47,000
 And we are about to see whether Trump delivers on his promises of creating a Bitcoin strategic reserves for the United States.

327
00:37:47,000 --> 00:37:58,000
 There is a U.S. Senator from Wyoming, her name is Cynthia Lummis, who does excellent work in that area and who has come up with a proposal.

328
00:37:58,000 --> 00:38:10,000
 In a nutshell, the proposal could lead to the elimination of sovereign debt through the use of a Bitcoin strategic reserve.

329
00:38:10,000 --> 00:38:11,000
 And that's of course all.

330
00:38:11,000 --> 00:38:16,000
 Way too complex to lay it out in one minute here at the table.

331
00:38:16,000 --> 00:38:22,000
 But there are very interesting promising use cases potentially up there in the future.

332
00:38:22,000 --> 00:38:29,000
 And the interesting thing is this is all the advantage of the first mover.

333
00:38:29,000 --> 00:38:32,000
 So whoever does it first has the most benefit.

334
00:38:32,000 --> 00:38:47,000
 Just like MicroStrategy is probably far ahead of the game if ever any other company like Google, Apple, Meta, Microsoft would start jump on that train.

335
00:38:47,000 --> 00:38:51,000
 They would have a hard time ever catching a Michael Saylor's company.

336
00:38:51,000 --> 00:38:55,000
 And the same would be true for a nation state adopting Bitcoin.

337
00:38:55,000 --> 00:39:03,000
 Once a big one has started, then the others will only be able to collect the crumbs.

338
00:39:03,000 --> 00:39:07,000
 When we talk about donations, is El Salvador a good example?

339
00:39:07,000 --> 00:39:11,000
 They have started investing and keeping Bitcoin as a treasury reserve.

340
00:39:11,000 --> 00:39:14,000
 And so far it looks great for them.

341
00:39:14,000 --> 00:39:18,000
 Another pioneer just like Michael Saylor is the pioneer of corporate adoption.

342
00:39:18,000 --> 00:39:28,000
 Nayib Bukele, the president of El Salvador, is the first nation state adopter.

343
00:39:28,000 --> 00:39:35,000
 The first leader of a government that understood this, that put in the work to understood it.

344
00:39:35,000 --> 00:39:41,000
 And to put Bitcoin to work for the benefit of his country's finances.

345
00:39:41,000 --> 00:39:50,000
 And again, just like in the case of MicroStrategy, El Salvador is a small country.

346
00:39:50,000 --> 00:39:54,000
 MicroStrategy is a comparatively small company.

347
00:39:54,000 --> 00:40:00,000
 And in both cases, there was one person who understood the thing and was able to get this going.

348
00:40:00,000 --> 00:40:02,000
 Those are the pioneers.

349
00:40:02,000 --> 00:40:11,000
 And now I am curious to see who is going to be, who are going to be the next adopters in line.

350
00:40:11,000 --> 00:40:15,000
 I'm sure we'll be seeing much of that maybe in this coming year.

351
00:40:15,000 --> 00:40:24,000
 Michael Saylor says the year 2025 is the year of institutional adoption of Bitcoin as he sees it.

352
00:40:24,000 --> 00:40:26,000
 We mentioned Bitcoin.

353
00:40:26,000 --> 00:40:27,000
 We explained Bitcoin.

354
00:40:27,000 --> 00:40:28,000
 We explained why does it have value.

355
00:40:28,000 --> 00:40:32,000
 We explained how companies can acquire it and how nations can.

356
00:40:32,000 --> 00:40:38,000
 Can you touch on some challenges that Bitcoin is facing in the future or right now?

357
00:40:38,000 --> 00:40:39,000
 No.

358
00:40:39,000 --> 00:40:40,000
 No challenges?

359
00:40:40,000 --> 00:40:48,000
 I think the story is that Bitcoin comes to those who need to know.

360
00:40:48,000 --> 00:40:51,000
 That's another date from Michael Saylor.

361
00:40:51,000 --> 00:40:57,000
 And it means that you need to put in the work to understand it.

362
00:40:57,000 --> 00:41:02,000
 And once you do, then you will be able to benefit from it.

363
00:41:02,000 --> 00:41:05,000
 And if you don't, you don't have to.

364
00:41:05,000 --> 00:41:10,000
 Bitcoin is for anyone, but not for everyone.

365
00:41:10,000 --> 00:41:16,000
 And those who are willing to put in the work can benefit.

366
00:41:16,000 --> 00:41:19,000
 And those who don't, don't.

367
00:41:19,000 --> 00:41:24,000
 There is no particular challenge in the sense that no state can stop it.

368
00:41:24,000 --> 00:41:29,000
 States can close the on-ramps and the off-ramps.

369
00:41:29,000 --> 00:41:37,000
 What they will achieve by that is they will not stop Bitcoin or stop their people from using Bitcoin,

370
00:41:37,000 --> 00:41:41,000
 but they will exclude themselves from the benefits of Bitcoin.

371
00:41:41,000 --> 00:41:50,000
 So, either way, I don't see, I am very optimistic, I should say, about the future of this technology.

372
00:41:50,000 --> 00:41:56,000
 Finally, what is your vision for the future of education in the area of Bitcoin?

373
00:41:56,000 --> 00:42:00,000
 And how can students prepare for challenges and opportunities ahead of them?

374
00:42:00,000 --> 00:42:03,000
 That is a very dear topic to myself.

375
00:42:03,000 --> 00:42:12,000
 And I am advocating very much the inclusion of Bitcoin in the curricula of higher education

376
00:42:12,000 --> 00:42:17,000
 or generally of the formal educational system.

377
00:42:17,000 --> 00:42:26,000
 Just today I had a conversation in class with high school students who came to visit our college.

378
00:42:26,000 --> 00:42:33,000
 And my first warm-up question to them was, "What about money did you learn at school?"

379
00:42:33,000 --> 00:42:36,000
 Well, nothing.

380
00:42:36,000 --> 00:42:39,000
 Nobody teaches them anything about money.

381
00:42:39,000 --> 00:42:44,000
 And I think I have laid out in much detail how important knowing about money is

382
00:42:44,000 --> 00:42:50,000
 in order to safeguard yourself from its unexpected side effects.

383
00:42:50,000 --> 00:42:54,000
 So, what is important for young people is to study this.

384
00:42:54,000 --> 00:43:01,000
 And to study both how money works in the fiat sense

385
00:43:01,000 --> 00:43:06,000
 and what alternative do we have available in Bitcoin.

386
00:43:06,000 --> 00:43:10,000
 This is, in principle, something everybody can do themselves.

387
00:43:10,000 --> 00:43:19,000
 But it will be hard, honestly, to not fall for all the scams and for all the Ponzi schemes

388
00:43:19,000 --> 00:43:26,000
 and for all the poor information out there publicly available on sources like YouTube.

389
00:43:26,000 --> 00:43:31,000
 So, be careful and look for authentic sources.

390
00:43:31,000 --> 00:43:41,000
 Or, if you are lucky and your educational institution offers that, take a course that teaches you about money and Bitcoin.

391
00:43:41,000 --> 00:43:53,000
 I have pioneered this at RIT Croatia and I hope to put RIT Croatia on the map as the Bitcoin place, at least in the region of ex-Yugoslavia.

392
00:43:53,000 --> 00:44:04,000
 And it's going quite well right now because I'm not aware that any other school anywhere near us teaches something like that.

393
00:44:04,000 --> 00:44:12,000
 As a matter of fact, not even our mother campus in Rochester has a course like the one we have here in Zagreb.

394
00:44:12,000 --> 00:44:21,000
 Now, there is one more important thing: Bitcoin is for everyone in the sense that everyone should be studying this.

395
00:44:21,000 --> 00:44:27,000
 And not only students that study economics.

396
00:44:27,000 --> 00:44:36,000
 These should be students, sorry, every student should be studying Bitcoin because they are a young person.

397
00:44:36,000 --> 00:44:37,000
 That is the key.

398
00:44:37,000 --> 00:44:39,000
 It affects everybody.

399
00:44:39,000 --> 00:44:49,000
 It affects students of any of our programs, whether they be in web and mobile computing, whether they be in new media design or soon in cybersecurity.

400
00:44:49,000 --> 00:44:52,000
 All these people will every day deal with money.

401
00:44:52,000 --> 00:45:03,000
 They will deal with the same difficulties that every young person has to build a future to acquire wealth and to live a beautiful life.

402
00:45:03,000 --> 00:45:16,000
 And that is why it is inevitable that they study how that works under the conditions that they find in the 20s of the 21st century.

403
00:45:16,000 --> 00:45:18,000
 Professor, thank you very much for joining us today.

404
00:45:18,000 --> 00:45:23,000
 I wish you all the luck for the future education and transferring knowledge to young people.

405
00:45:23,000 --> 00:45:27,000
 And I'll be happy to have you for more technical lecture in the future.

406
00:45:27,000 --> 00:45:39,000
 I'd be happy to return in more detail because Bitcoin is something that requires a lot of responsibility from the user.

407
00:45:39,000 --> 00:45:43,000
 So it's a good thing that you mentioned technical topics.

408
00:45:43,000 --> 00:45:45,000
 Thank you for having me.

409
00:45:45,000 --> 00:45:48,000
 And I very much enjoyed talking about this as always.

410
00:45:48,000 --> 00:45:49,000
 Thank you.

411
00:45:49,000 --> 00:45:50,000
 Thank you.

